Here's the full migration analysis and replacement code.

## Pattern Classification

| Location | Pattern | Issue on .NET 8 |
|----------|---------|-----------------|
| `RunLoop` `while(true)` | Cancellable work loop | No way to stop cooperatively |
| `_newEvent.WaitOne()` | Blocking call interruption | `Thread.Interrupt` won't reliably wake it |
| `Stop()` â†’ `Thread.Interrupt()` | Obsolete API | `SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9, unreliable |
| `Stop()` â†’ `Thread.Abort()` | Removed API | **`PlatformNotSupportedException`** on .NET 8 |

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly ManualResetEvent _newEvent = new ManualResetEvent(false);
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new Queue<string>();
    private readonly object _lock = new object();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
    private Thread? _thread;

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var token = _cts.Token;
        var handles = new WaitHandle[] { _newEvent, token.WaitHandle };

        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // WaitAny returns index: 0 = new event, 1 = cancellation
            int signaled = WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles);
            if (signaled == 1)
                break;

            _newEvent.Reset();

            // Drain all queued items (fixes race where multiple
            // Enqueue calls signal before one WaitOne wakes)
            while (true)
            {
                string? item;
                lock (_lock)
                {
                    if (_queue.Count == 0)
                        break;
                    item = _queue.Dequeue();
                }
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();           // signals token.WaitHandle â†’ wakes WaitAny
        _thread?.Join(5000);     // wait up to 5s for clean exit
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
        _newEvent.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Key Changes Explained

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `while (true)` | `while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)` | Cooperative exit check |
| `_newEvent.WaitOne()` | `WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles)` | Wakes on **either** new work or cancellation |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Cancel signals the `WaitHandle`, unblocking `WaitAny` immediately |
| `Thread.Abort()` | *(removed)* | Unnecessary â€” cancellation guarantees the loop exits |
| Single `Dequeue` per wake | Drain loop | Fixes pre-existing race: multiple `Enqueue` â†’ one `Set` |

## Pitfalls to Watch

1. **`Thread.Abort` â†’ `PlatformNotSupportedException`** â€” This is the hard blocker. The fallback `Abort()` in the original `Stop()` simply throws on .NET 8.

2. **`Thread.Interrupt` is unreliable even where it compiles** â€” It only works if the thread is in `WaitSleepJoin` state *at that exact moment*. With `WaitHandle.WaitAny` + `token.WaitHandle`, cancellation is deterministic.

3. **Lost events in the original code** â€” If `Enqueue` is called twice before `RunLoop` wakes, `Set()` is idempotent on an already-signaled `ManualResetEvent`. The second item stays queued but only one `Dequeue` runs. The drain loop above fixes this.

4. **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** â€” It holds timer/callback resources. The `IDisposable` implementation ensures cleanup.

5. **Don't remove `Thread.Join`** â€” `Join` works identically on .NET 8; it's the safe way to wait for thread completion after signaling cancellation.
